events.description: The Byzantine–Venetian treaty of 1277 is concluded, stipulating a two-year truce and renewing Venetian commercial privileges in the Byzantine Empire.
events.html: • 1277 – The Byzantine–Venetian treaty of 1277 is concluded, stipulating a two-year truce and renewing Venetian commercial privileges in the Byzantine Empire.[1]

events.description: A Mongol victory at the Battle of Yamen ends the Song dynasty in China.
events.html: • 1279 – A Mongol victory at the Battle of Yamen ends the Song dynasty in China.

events.description: The Statute of Rhuddlan incorporates the Principality of Wales into England.
events.html: • 1284 – The Statute of Rhuddlan incorporates the Principality of Wales into England.[2]

events.description: Frederick III of Habsburg is the last Holy Roman Emperor crowned by medieval tradition in Rome by Pope Nicholas V.
events.html: • 1452 – Frederick III of Habsburg is the last Holy Roman Emperor crowned by medieval tradition in Rome by Pope Nicholas V.[3]

events.description: The Edict of Amboise is signed, ending the first phase of the French Wars of Religion and granting certain freedoms to the Huguenots.
events.html: • 1563 – The Edict of Amboise is signed, ending the first phase of the French Wars of Religion and granting certain freedoms to the Huguenots.

events.description: The House of Commons of England passes an act abolishing the House of Lords, declaring it "useless and dangerous to the people of England".
events.html: • 1649 – The House of Commons of England passes an act abolishing the House of Lords, declaring it "useless and dangerous to the people of England".

entities.name: History of reform of the House of Lords

events.description: Explorer Robert Cavelier de La Salle, searching for the mouth of the Mississippi River, is murdered by his own men.
events.html: • 1687 – Explorer Robert Cavelier de La Salle, searching for the mouth of the Mississippi River, is murdered by his own men.

events.description: Charles IV, king of Spain, abdicates after riots and a popular revolt at the winter palace Aranjuez. His son, Ferdinand VII, takes the throne.
events.html: • 1808 – Charles IV, king of Spain, abdicates after riots and a popular revolt at the winter palace Aranjuez. His son, Ferdinand VII, takes the throne.[4]

events.description: The Cortes of Cádiz promulgates the Spanish Constitution of 1812.
events.html: • 1812 – The Cortes of Cádiz promulgates the Spanish Constitution of 1812.

events.description: American explorer Benjamin Morrell departed Antarctica after a voyage later plagued by claims of fraud.
events.html: • 1824 – American explorer Benjamin Morrell departed Antarctica after a voyage later plagued by claims of fraud.[5]

events.description: First documented bank heist in U.S. history, when burglars stole $245,000 (1831 values) from the City Bank (now Citibank) on Wall Street. Most of the money was recovered.
events.html: • 1831 – First documented bank heist in U.S. history, when burglars stole $245,000 (1831 values) from the City Bank (now Citibank) on Wall Street.[6] Most of the money was recovered.

entities.name: 1831 City Bank of New York theft

events.description: American Civil War: The Battle of Bentonville begins. By the end of the battle two days later, Confederate forces had retreated from Four Oaks, North Carolina.
events.html: • 1865 – American Civil War: The Battle of Bentonville begins. By the end of the battle two days later, Confederate forces had retreated from Four Oaks, North Carolina.

events.description: Louis Riel declares a provisional government in Saskatchewan, beginning the North-West Rebellion.
events.html: • 1885 – Louis Riel declares a provisional government in Saskatchewan, beginning the North-West Rebellion.

events.description: The US Congress establishes time zones and approves daylight saving time.
events.html: • 1918 – The US Congress establishes time zones and approves daylight saving time.

events.description: The United States Senate rejects the Treaty of Versailles for the second time (the first time was on November 19, 1919).
events.html: • 1920 – The United States Senate rejects the Treaty of Versailles for the second time (the first time was on November 19, 1919).

events.description: Irish War of Independence: One of the biggest engagements of the war takes place at Crossbarry, County Cork. About 100 Irish Republican Army (IRA) volunteers escape an attempt by over 1,300 British forces to encircle them.
events.html: • 1921 – Irish War of Independence: One of the biggest engagements of the war takes place at Crossbarry, County Cork. About 100 Irish Republican Army (IRA) volunteers escape an attempt by over 1,300 British forces to encircle them.

events.description: Governor Fred B. Balzar signs a bill legalizing gambling in Nevada.
events.html: • 1931 – Governor Fred B. Balzar signs a bill legalizing gambling in Nevada.

events.description: The Sydney Harbour Bridge is opened.
events.html: • 1932 – The Sydney Harbour Bridge is opened.[7]

events.description: Frank Nitti, the Chicago Outfit Boss after Al Capone, commits suicide at the Chicago Central Railyard.
events.html: • 1943 – Frank Nitti, the Chicago Outfit Boss after Al Capone, commits suicide at the Chicago Central Railyard.

events.description: World War II: The German army occupies Hungary.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: The German army occupies Hungary.

events.description: World War II: Off the coast of Japan, a dive bomber hits the aircraft carrier USS Franklin, killing 724 of her crew. Badly damaged, the ship is able to return to the US under her own power.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: Off the coast of Japan, a dive bomber hits the aircraft carrier USS Franklin, killing 724 of her crew. Badly damaged, the ship is able to return to the US under her own power.

events.description: World War II: Adolf Hitler issues his "Nero Decree" ordering all industries, military installations, shops, transportation facilities, and communications facilities in Germany to be destroyed.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: Adolf Hitler issues his "Nero Decree" ordering all industries, military installations, shops, transportation facilities, and communications facilities in Germany to be destroyed.

events.description: French Guiana, Guadeloupe, Martinique, and Réunion become overseas départements of France.
events.html: • 1946 – French Guiana, Guadeloupe, Martinique, and Réunion become overseas départements of France.

events.description: The Monarch Underwear Company fire leaves 24 dead and 15 injured.
events.html: • 1958 – The Monarch Underwear Company fire leaves 24 dead and 15 injured.

events.description: The Algerian War of Independence ends.
events.html: • 1962 – The Algerian War of Independence ends.

events.description: Over 500,000 Brazilians attend the March of the Family with God for Liberty, in protest against the government of João Goulart and against communism.
events.html: • 1964 – Over 500,000 Brazilians attend the March of the Family with God for Liberty, in protest against the government of João Goulart and against communism.

entities.name: March of the Family with God for Liberty

events.description: The wreck of the SS Georgiana, valued at over $50,000,000 and said to have been the most powerful Confederate cruiser, is discovered by teenage diver and pioneer underwater archaeologist E. Lee Spence, exactly 102 years after its destruction.
events.html: • 1965 – The wreck of the SS Georgiana, valued at over $50,000,000 and said to have been the most powerful Confederate cruiser, is discovered by teenage diver and pioneer underwater archaeologist E. Lee Spence, exactly 102 years after its destruction.

events.description: The 385-metre-tall (1,263 ft) TV-mast at Emley Moor transmitting station, United Kingdom, collapses due to ice build-up.
events.html: • 1969 – The 385-metre-tall (1,263 ft) TV-mast at Emley Moor transmitting station, United Kingdom, collapses due to ice build-up.

events.description: The United States House of Representatives begins broadcasting its day-to-day business via the cable television network C-SPAN.
events.html: • 1979 – The United States House of Representatives begins broadcasting its day-to-day business via the cable television network C-SPAN.

events.description: Falklands War: Argentinian forces land on South Georgia Island, precipitating war with the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1982 – Falklands War: Argentinian forces land on South Georgia Island, precipitating war with the United Kingdom.

events.description: The Egyptian flag is raised at Taba, marking the end of Israeli occupation since the Six Days War in 1967 and the Egypt–Israel peace treaty in 1979.
events.html: • 1989 – The Egyptian flag is raised at Taba, marking the end of Israeli occupation since the Six Days War in 1967 and the Egypt–Israel peace treaty in 1979.

events.description: The ethnic clashes of Târgu Mureș begin four days after the anniversary of the Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire.
events.html: • 1990 – The ethnic clashes of Târgu Mureș begin four days after the anniversary of the Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire.

entities.name: Revolutions of 1848 in the Austrian Empire

events.description: An Ariana Afghan Airlines Boeing 727 crashes on approach to Kabul International Airport, killing all 45 on board.
events.html: • 1998 – An Ariana Afghan Airlines Boeing 727 crashes on approach to Kabul International Airport, killing all 45 on board.[8]

events.description: United States President George W. Bush addresses the nation, announcing the invasion of Iraq.
events.html: • 2003 – United States President George W. Bush addresses the nation, announcing the invasion of Iraq.[9]

events.description: Catalina affair: A Swedish DC-3 shot down by a Soviet MiG-15 in 1952 over the Baltic Sea is finally recovered after years of work.
events.html: • 2004 – Catalina affair: A Swedish DC-3 shot down by a Soviet MiG-15 in 1952 over the Baltic Sea is finally recovered after years of work.

events.description: March 19 Shooting Incident: The Republic of China (Taiwan) president Chen Shui-bian is shot just before the country's presidential election on March 20.
events.html: • 2004 – March 19 Shooting Incident: The Republic of China (Taiwan) president Chen Shui-bian is shot just before the country's presidential election on March 20.

events.description: GRB 080319B: A cosmic burst that is the farthest object visible to the naked eye is briefly observed.
events.html: • 2008 – GRB 080319B: A cosmic burst that is the farthest object visible to the naked eye is briefly observed.

events.description: Libyan Civil War: After the failure of Muammar Gaddafi's forces to take Benghazi, the French Air Force launches Opération Harmattan, beginning foreign military intervention in Libya.
events.html: • 2011 – Libyan Civil War: After the failure of Muammar Gaddafi's forces to take Benghazi, the French Air Force launches Opération Harmattan, beginning foreign military intervention in Libya.

events.description: A series of bombings and shootings kills at least 98 people and injures 240 others across Iraq.
events.html: • 2013 – A series of bombings and shootings kills at least 98 people and injures 240 others across Iraq.

events.description: Flydubai Flight 981 crashes while attempting to land at Rostov-on-Don international airport, killing all 62 on board.
events.html: • 2016 – Flydubai Flight 981 crashes while attempting to land at Rostov-on-Don international airport, killing all 62 on board.

events.description: An explosion occurs in Taksim Square in Istanbul, Turkey, killing five people and injuring 36.
events.html: • 2016 – An explosion occurs in Taksim Square in Istanbul, Turkey, killing five people and injuring 36.

events.description: The first President of Kazakhstan, Nursultan Nazarbayev, resigns from office after nearly three decades, leaving Senate Chairman Kassym-Jomart Tokayev as the acting President and successor.
events.html: • 2019 – The first President of Kazakhstan, Nursultan Nazarbayev, resigns from office after nearly three decades, leaving Senate Chairman Kassym-Jomart Tokayev as the acting President and successor.[10]

entities.name: Chairman of the Senate of Kazakhstan

events.description: The Swiss Government brokers a deal for UBS to buy out rival Credit Suisse in an attempt to calm the 2023 banking crisis.
